<H3> <TI>   Foreign Affairs Spokesman on Hungarian Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Affairs Spokesman on Hungarian Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1105191194 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 1618 GMT 11 May 94 
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1105191194 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Bucharest</LOCATION>, ROMPRES, 11/5/1994 -- Referring to the 
first round of the elections recently held in <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION>, the 
spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION>Romanian Ministry of Foreign Affairs</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Mircea 
Geoana</PERSON> told a press conference on 11 <DATE>May</DATE> that "in order to have 
a complete and definitive picture of the <ORGANIZATION>Hungarian Parliament</ORGANIZATION>'s 
composition, and, consequently, of the government to be 
appointed, we need to see the results of the second round. It 
is obvious however that the Socialist Party is heading for 
victory." 
  About the Romanian-Hungarian relations once socialists 
accede 
to power, the <ORGANIZATION>Romanian Foreign Ministry</ORGANIZATION> spokesman said the 
socialists' statements in the pre-election period were already 
known. "They voiced a constructive approach the Socialist Party 
intended to have if, elections over, they gained access to the 
ruling structures," <PERSON>Mircea Geoana</PERSON> said. He also said that the 
Romanian side received such statements with interest and that 
"the Romanian authorities are waiting to see the outcome of the 
electoral process in <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION>, with a view to identifying, 
jointly with the new <ORGANIZATION>Hungarian Government</ORGANIZATION>, the concrete means to 
continue the negotiations on the framework political treaty, and 
on the bilateral relations as a whole." 
  According to information furnished by the spokesman for the 
<ORGANIZATION>Romanian Ministry of Foreign Affairs</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Mircea Geoana</PERSON>, the 
president of the <ORGANIZATION>European Parliament</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Egon Klepsch</ORGANIZATION> is expected 
on an official visit to <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> on <DATE>16-17 May this year</DATE> at the 
invitation of the <ORGANIZATION>Romanian Parliament</ORGANIZATION>. The head of the <ORGANIZATION>European 
Parliament</ORGANIZATION> will have meetings with the speakers of the two 
houses of the <ORGANIZATION>Romanian Parliament</ORGANIZATION>, with members of the <ORGANIZATION>Foreign 
Policy Committees</ORGANIZATION>, and with the Romanian parliamentary 
delegation to the <ORGANIZATION>European Parliament</ORGANIZATION>. He will also meet with 
leaders of the parliamentary groups, the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION>Council 
for Economic Coordination</ORGANIZATION>, Strategy and Reform, and the <ORGANIZATION>Minister 
of Foreign Affairs</ORGANIZATION>. Egon Klepsch will deliver a speech before a 
joint sitting of parliament, and will be received by the 
president of <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION>. 
  The <ORGANIZATION>Foreign Ministry</ORGANIZATION> spokesman also informed the press that 
the president of the <ORGANIZATION>European Commission</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Jacques Delors</PERSON>, will 
be the guest of <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> on 2-4 <DATE>June</DATE>, at the invitation of Prime 
Minister <PERSON>Nicolae Vacaroiu</PERSON>. 
  In the same line, the spokesman announced that the <ORGANIZATION>European 
Parliament</ORGANIZATION> approved in its plenary meeting the recommendation of 
the <ORGANIZATION>European Commission</ORGANIZATION> for a ECU 125,000,000 credit to <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION>, 
representing the quota underwritten by the <ORGANIZATION>European Union</ORGANIZATION> from 
the <MONEY>$300,000,000</MONEY> loan officially applied for by the <ORGANIZATION>Romanian 
Government</ORGANIZATION> to the G-24 with the purpose of compensating the 
balance of payments and financing the economic reform over 
1993-1994. 

</TEXT>

