<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Spokesman Cited on Treaties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Spokesman Cited on Treaties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2004181394 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 1620 GMT 20 Apr 94 
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2004181394 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Bucharest ROMPRES</LOCATION>, 20/4/1994 -- Foreign Ministry 
Spokesman <PERSON>Mircea Geoana</PERSON> made a few points on news items in the 
Romanian media on the Romanian-Hungarian treaty, during a news 
conference he held in <LOCATION>Bucharest</LOCATION> on 20 <DATE>April</DATE>. The news items 
claimed that "sources at the <ORGANIZATION>Foreign Ministry</ORGANIZATION> and the presidency 
said that, pursuant to <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION>NATO</ORGANIZATION> pressures, the basic 
Romanian-Hungarian political treaty will be signed by 1 <DATE>July, 
1994</DATE>." 
  <PERSON>Mircea Geoana</PERSON> denied the existence of such an understanding 
and said that as far as <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> was concerned, it was interested 
to conclude the political treaty with <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION> the soonest. 
"Even before the <LOCATION>Paris</LOCATION> conference or <DATE>26-27 May</DATE>, when the 
`stability' pact initiated by <PERSON>Balladur</PERSON> is launched, we would 
like to do it," said <PERSON>Mircea Geoana</PERSON>. He added that <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION> has 
not stated its stand on the proposals advanced long ago by the 
<ORGANIZATION>Romanian Foreign Ministry</ORGANIZATION> regarding the outstanding issues. "If 
we got an answer and were able to agree on a new round of 
negotiations, this would be a positive element in the actuation 
of the Romanian-Hungarian political dialogue," he said. 
  Regarding the issue of lifting the embargo against the 
<ORGANIZATION>Federal Republic of Yugoslavia</ORGANIZATION>, "from what we know this is not 
envisaged for now" -- Foreign Ministry Spokesman <PERSON>Mircea Geoana</PERSON> 
said, referring to the "official launch" of the joint demarche 
of <LOCATION>Greece</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Bulgaria</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> in this respect. The <ORGANIZATION>Foreign 
Ministry</ORGANIZATION> spokesman said such a demarche ought to be made at the 
right time, when the process of political negotiations reaches a 
congenial stage. "In keeping with the evolution of the 
negotiations between the Bosnian conflicting parties, a decision 
will be analyzed and made by all parties concerned", he said, 
adding that <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION> showed interest in the demarche, while 
<LOCATION>Ukraine</LOCATION> did not state its stand. 
  The idea of a joint demarche of <LOCATION>Greece</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Bulgaria</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> 
for the lifting of the embargo on the <ORGANIZATION>Federal Republic of 
Yugoslavia</ORGANIZATION> was launched during the <LOCATION>Bucharest</LOCATION> visit by the Greek 
foreign minister a few weeks ago. The initiative pursues the 
easing of the negative effects emerged following the application 
of the <ORGANIZATION>UN</ORGANIZATION> sanctions by the countries neighbouring <LOCATION>ex-Yugoslavia</LOCATION>. 
  The prime minister of the Grand Duchy of <LOCATION>Luxembourg</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Jacques 
Smiter</PERSON>, will make an official visit in <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> over <DATE>April 24-26</DATE> 
at the invitation of the Romanian Prime Minister <PERSON>Nicolae 
Vacaroiu</PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION>Romanian Foreign Ministry</ORGANIZATION> spokesman also said. 
  The agenda of the visit includes official talks with the 
Romanian premier, interviews with Romanian President <PERSON>Ion 
Iliescu</PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON>Oliviu Gherman</PERSON>, Chamber of Deputies 
Speaker <PERSON>Adrian Nastase</PERSON>. 
  On the occasion of the visit, an inter-governmental 
agreement 
of cooperation in the fields of culture, education, science and 
sport will be signed. 
  The postponement of the signing of the basic political 
treaty 
between <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION>Federal Republic</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>Yugoslavia</LOCATION>, first 
scheduled to take place while Yugoslav Federal President <PERSON>Zoran 
Lilic</PERSON> was in <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> for the <ORGANIZATION>Crans Montana Forum</ORGANIZATION>, stirred the 
interest of the journalists who attended the <ORGANIZATION>Foreign Ministry</ORGANIZATION> 
briefing on 20 <DATE>April</DATE>. Confirming President <PERSON>Lilic</PERSON> would not 
attend the Forum because of the tense situation in <LOCATION>Bosnia</LOCATION>, 
<PERSON>Mircea Geoana</PERSON> said the official document would be signed only 
after the two parties agreed on all issues. "It is an important 
political document with a neighbour state, that has to fall in 
line with the whole of the political treaties <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> is 
concluding with other states of the world," he added. "It is 
not to be achieved upon conjunctural bases, statuting instead 
the format of bilateral relations in all spheres." 
  Referring to the conflict in <LOCATION>Gorazde</LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>Romanian Foreign 
Ministry</ORGANIZATION> spokesman reiterated <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION>'s constant stand relying 
upon the principle of using the whole range of 
political-diplomatic means to induce the conflicting parties to 
go on negotiating. "We follow with worry the events in <LOCATION>Gorazde</LOCATION> 
and see the high rate of contacts and statements by all parties 
concerned, which leaves room for optimism," <PERSON>Geoana</PERSON> said. 

</TEXT>

