<H3> <TI>   Comments by Moldova's Snegur Draw Reaction </TI></H3>
<H4>   Party Officials Comment </H4>
<F P=102> AU0702172694 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 1400 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0702172694 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Bucharest ROMPRES</LOCATION>, 7/2/1994 -- <PERSON>Dumitru Paslaru</PERSON>, 
spokesman of the ruling party of Social Democracy of <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> 
(<ORGANIZATION>PDSR</ORGANIZATION>), said developments in the Republic of <LOCATION>Moldova</LOCATION>, the 
reconsideration of the stands of important political 
personalities there and their statements rendered delicate the 
continuation of the political relations and the rapprochement 
between <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> and that state. In an interview with ROMPRES, 
<PERSON>Paslaru</PERSON> added that the <ORGANIZATION>PDSR</ORGANIZATION> considered the statements made by 
<PERSON>Snegur</PERSON> [president of the Republic of <LOCATION>Moldova</LOCATION>] and <PERSON>Motpan</PERSON> 
[president of the <ORGANIZATION>Agrarian Democratic Party of Moldova</ORGANIZATION>] to be 
inciting, offending the Romanians everywhere, an attempt at the 
country's national integrity, an obvious disconsideration of 
public opinion of the Romanian majority in the present Republic 
of <LOCATION>Moldova</LOCATION>. "We however hope these statements are just a 
temporary element in the political climate of the Republic of 
<LOCATION>Moldova</LOCATION>. These statements should better not turn into ruling 
theses and the optimistic tone of our relations of so far should 
be resumed," the <ORGANIZATION>PDSR</ORGANIZATION> spokesman also said. 
  The <ORGANIZATION>Romanian National Unity Party</ORGANIZATION> [<ORGANIZATION>PUNR</ORGANIZATION>] Vice-President 
<PERSON>Cornel Brahas</PERSON> assesses as a mistake the fact that the Romanian 
authorities recognized officially "this shadow state in 
<LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION>'s historical territory. It is an open attempt at our 
integrity and a tragical betrayal of the Romanian nation. No 
matter what eastern or western chancellories encouraged <PERSON>Snegur</PERSON> 
to assume this terrible burden, we must not give in to 
defeatism," <PERSON>Cornel Brahas</PERSON> said. 
  "I have not been taken by surprise by this statement made by 
<PERSON>Mr. Mircea Snegur</PERSON>, a good Romanian speaker but not an equally 
good Romanian. It was prepared by other political actions which 
we ignored when we did not encourage," said Professor <PERSON>Ion Coja</PERSON>, 
an outstanding member of the <ORGANIZATION>Agrarian Democratic Party of 
Romania</ORGANIZATION> (PDAR). "What's even worse is that, in a concerted 
manner, some sort of declaration of annexation of <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION>'s 
territory to the former <ORGANIZATION>USSR</ORGANIZATION> is also launched. It is high time 
that the president of <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION>, the parliament and government 
took at long last a stand that should not be criticized by the 
future generations of Romanians on either bank of the Prut," 
Professor <PERSON>Ion Coja</PERSON> said. 
  "The <ORGANIZATION>National Council of Reintegration</ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION>National 
Party 
of Reintegration</ORGANIZATION> have decided to `back' <PERSON>Mircea Snegur</PERSON>, 
organizing the participation in the referendum of the more than 
one million refugees or their descendants, either Romanians, 
Jews, Germans, Poles," said <PERSON>Mircea Druc</PERSON>, former prime minister 
of the Republic of <LOCATION>Moldova</LOCATION>, now president of the <ORGANIZATION>National Party 
of Reintegration</ORGANIZATION>. "A referendum of all those who were forced to 
leave their native land following the Soviet invasion. In a 
near future, we will convene also a world congress of all 
refugees because we too, want to be a part of `<PERSON>Snegur</PERSON>'s people' 
summoned to the referendum," <PERSON>Mircea Druc</PERSON> said. 
  "<PERSON>Mircea Snegur</PERSON> has proved he has remained a cent [as 
received] percent communist and no longer thinks, even for a 
moment, that he is Romanian," said <PERSON>Ion Diaconescu</PERSON>, 
vice-president of the <ORGANIZATION>Christian Democratic National Peasant 
Party</ORGANIZATION>. 
  "For him, the notion of Romanian is completely subordinated 
to the political creed for which he has campaigned for a 
lifetime. His theses are communist, they were <ORGANIZATION>Stalin</ORGANIZATION>'s as well 
and he keeps them because he grew up with them. 
  "Nobody imposes <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION>'s union with <LOCATION>Bessarabia</LOCATION> by force, 
but 
to go as far as declaring that Romanians and Moldovans are 
different peoples is a nonsense launched by communists which 
<PERSON>Mircea Snegur</PERSON>, as a truthful disciple, has adopted." 

</TEXT>

