<H3> <TI>   Turkey Favors Nation's Admission to NATO </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1201195994 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 1813 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1201195994 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Bucharest ROMPRES</LOCATION>, 12/01/1994 -- <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION>'s 
President <PERSON>Ion Iliescu</PERSON> received a letter of reply from <LOCATION>Turkey</LOCATION>'s 
President <PERSON>Suleyman Demirel</PERSON> saying that <LOCATION>Turkey</LOCATION> favours <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION>'s 
application to joint <ORGANIZATION>NATO</ORGANIZATION> and will back the alliance's decisions 
meeting these aspirations. 
  The letter stresses <LOCATION>Turkey</LOCATION>'s admiration of the progress 
marked by <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> since <DATE>1990</DATE> and the satisfaction at the fine 
and close collaboration within the <ORGANIZATION>North-Atlantic Cooperation 
Council</ORGANIZATION>, as well as the interest confirmed by <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> in the 
collaboration with that forum that has brought <ORGANIZATION>NATO</ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> 
closer. 
  "We see the Partnership for Peace initiative as an 
operational formula in this period of transition and believe it 
will help enhancing the security, stability and fertile 
cooperation in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> and around it," the <DATE>January 5, 1994</DATE> letter 
by <LOCATION>Turkey</LOCATION>'s president reads. 

</TEXT>

