<H3> <TI>   Iliescu on Ties, Former Yugoslavia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Iliescu on Ties, Former Yugoslavia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1005191494 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 1808 GMT 10 May 94 
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1005191494 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Bucharest ROMPRES</LOCATION>, 10/5/1994 -- In the evening of 
10 <DATE>May</DATE> President <PERSON>Ion Iliescu</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> offered an official 
dinner in honor of Albanian President <PERSON>Sali Berisha</PERSON> and of the 
delegation that accompanied him on his visit to <LOCATION>Bucharest</LOCATION>. On 
this occasion Presidents <PERSON>Ion Iliescu</PERSON> and <PERSON>Sali Berisha</PERSON> held 
toasts. 
  In his toast, the head of the Romanian state said that 
"after 
the instatement of democratic regimes in our countries, 
favorable conditions were put in place for the Romanian-Albanian 
relations." In his opinion, the political treaty and the other 
cooperation documents to be signed during the Albanian 
president's visit express the political will of the sides for a 
fruitful long-term cooperation. 
  Mentioning <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Albania</LOCATION>'s concern about the conflict 
tearing apart the former Yugoslav space, the head of the 
Romanian state said: "It is sad that momentary circumstances, 
generated by the dismemberment of former <LOCATION>Yugoslavia</LOCATION>, that 
certain resentments, some of them probably motivated, should lie 
at the root of a tragedy and be now the greatest hurdle in the 
way of a political settlement in the area." The Romanian 
president underlined that <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> pronounces for a rational and 
responsible attitude on the part of all the leading factors in 
the area so that confrontation is renounced. President <PERSON>Iliescu</PERSON> 
pleaded for further support to the efforts of the international 
community in achieving peace. "The alternative to peace, to 
dialogue is cannot be but the extension of the conflict with 
enormous suffering for the peoples of former <LOCATION>Yugoslavia</LOCATION> and the 
risk of involving other states," the president of <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> said, 
who also reiterated <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION>'s "firm support for the actions 
directed towards finding a political solution, for the 
reinstatement of trust and understanding." "We wish to give the 
Romanian-Albanian relations a new impetus, to act in such a way 
as to forge exemplary economic, political, cultural, and 
spiritual ties between our peoples," the president of <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> 
also said. 

</TEXT>

