<H3> <TI>   Romania's Melescanu Signs NATO Partnership Document </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2601175594 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 1748 GMT 26 Jan 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2601175594 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Bucharest</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>ROMPRES</LOCATION>, 26/1/1994 -- Romanian Foreign 
Minister <PERSON>Teodor Melescanu</PERSON> signed on <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> <TIME>afternoon</TIME> [26 
<DATE>January</DATE>] the framework document concerning <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION>'s 
participation in the Partnership for Peace, an initiative 
launched at the <ORGANIZATION>NATO</ORGANIZATION> summit on <DATE>January 10-11</DATE>. The signing 
ceremony which took place in the <ORGANIZATION>NATO Council</ORGANIZATION> room was attended 
by <ORGANIZATION>NATO</ORGANIZATION> Assistant Secretary General <PERSON>Amedeo de Franchis</PERSON> and by 
the permanent representatives to the <ORGANIZATION>North Atlantic Council</ORGANIZATION> of 
the 16 member countries. 
  Due to this political act, which succeeds the acceptance of 
the invitation to the Partnership for Peace expressed by 
Romanian President <PERSON>Ion Iliescu</PERSON> in a statement on <DATE>January 11</DATE>, 
<LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> has become officially the first country to be engaged in 
the new cooperation pattern with the <ORGANIZATION>NATO</ORGANIZATION>. 
  At the signing ceremony, <PERSON>Amedeo de Franchis</PERSON> and <PERSON>Teodor 
Melescanu</PERSON> read out brief speeches stressing the political 
significance of the moment and expressing hope that the 
Partnership for Peace would contribute to the consolidation of 
the security and stability in whole <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>. Romanian Foreign 
Minister <PERSON>Melescanu</PERSON> underlined that <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> committed itself with 
all faith and responsibility to the new relation with <ORGANIZATION>NATO</ORGANIZATION> and 
with the <ORGANIZATION>NATO</ORGANIZATION> member countries, a relation considered by <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> 
as a preliminary and preparatory stage to <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION>'s future 
membership to <ORGANIZATION>NATO</ORGANIZATION>'s political and military structures. 
  Previous to the signing ceremony, the Romanian minister of 
foreign affairs had an interview with <PERSON>Amedeo de Franchis</PERSON> and met 
also with the permanent representatives to the <ORGANIZATION>North Atlantic 
Council</ORGANIZATION> of the 16 <ORGANIZATION>NATO</ORGANIZATION> member countries. 
  The <ORGANIZATION>NATO</ORGANIZATION> Assistant Secretary General <PERSON>Amedeo de Franchis</PERSON> 
saluted the "historic moment" when <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> became the first 
"cooperation partner" of the alliance, through the signing the 
framework document of the <ORGANIZATION>Partnership for Peace</ORGANIZATION>. 
  In a speech on <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> in <LOCATION>Brussels</LOCATION>, in the presence of 
Romanian Foreign Minister <PERSON>Teodor Melescanu</PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION>NATO</ORGANIZATION> assistant 
secretary general praised the courage and decision proven by the 
Romanian people in his fight for liberty. Today, <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> 
experiences a difficult process of political and economic reform 
in the interior but, at the same time, it works for the creation 
of new security relations in the exterior, said <PERSON>Amedeo de 
Franchis</PERSON>. 

</TEXT>

