<H3> <TI>   Iliescu Letter Seeks Admission to NATO </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0801191294 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 1742 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0801191294 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<FÊP=106> ["Romanian President's Letter to the <ORGANIZATION>Heads of State</ORGANIZATION> or </F>
Government of the <ORGANIZATION>NATO Member Countries</ORGANIZATION> and to the <ORGANIZATION>NATO</ORGANIZATION> General 
Secretariat" -- ROMPRES headline] 
  [Text] <LOCATION>Bucharest ROMPRES</LOCATION>, 7/1/1994 -- "Before the high 
level meeting of the <ORGANIZATION>NATO</ORGANIZATION> countries scheduled for 10 <DATE>January 
1994</DATE>, I should like to reassert <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION>'s position on the 
alliance and reconfirm the constant interest of my country to 
become a full member of the organization. I have expressed this 
interest on various occasions, including in the letter I 
addressed on 18 <DATE>September 1993</DATE> to the <ORGANIZATION>NATO General Secretariat</ORGANIZATION>, 
to <PERSON>Mr. Manfred Woerner</PERSON>. 
  "<LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> considers the <ORGANIZATION>North Atlantic Alliance</ORGANIZATION>, that has 
proved its ability to adjust to the new realities emerged after 
the close of the Cold War, as being the only organization apt to 
ensure stability on the European continent and guarantee the 
values of democracy and the state of law. 
  "I have received with special interest the `Partnership for 
Peace' proposal, perceived in <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> as being an important 
preliminary stage in the process of the country's full 
integration into the <ORGANIZATION>NATO</ORGANIZATION> structures. My country has shown 
willing to participate in this new form of cooperation, with 
respect of the requirements imposed by the status of member of 
the alliance. 
  "I would like to use this occasion to reassert <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION>'s 
strong conviction that, as an European state, it has a rightful 
place into <ORGANIZATION>NATO</ORGANIZATION>. 
  "In analyzing our request, please take into account 
<LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION>'s 
vital interests of security, that have been given new dimensions 
following the recent political developments in the areas in the 
proximity of my country. 
  "Moreover, <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> is resolute to get more actively involved 
in ensuring stability in the region and in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> in general, it 
is willing to assume all responsibilities it would have as a 
member of the alliance. 
  "I am sure that <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION>'s integration into <ORGANIZATION>NATO</ORGANIZATION> would offer 
us security guarantees absolutely necessary to create conditions 
adequate for translation into practice the democratic 
transformations and the economic reform <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> has firmly 
committed to. 
  "In my outlook, to be a member of <ORGANIZATION>NATO</ORGANIZATION> is an essential 
constituent of the global process of integration of <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> in 
Euro-Atlantic structures (<ORGANIZATION>NATO</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>WEU</ORGANIZATION> [Western European Union], 
the <LOCATION>European Union</LOCATION>, and the Council of <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>), this is the 
essential objective of the Romanian foreign policy. 
  "I hope that during the debates to be held at the high level 
meeting in <LOCATION>Brussels</LOCATION> you will consider the position of my 
country, on which all political parties in <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Parliament</ORGANIZATION>, 
the whole Romanian people, have agreed." 

</TEXT>

