<H3> <TI>   Belgium's Claes Meets Iliescu, Ends Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Belgium's Claes Meets Iliescu, Ends Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0804193294 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 1555 GMT 8 Apr 94 
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0804193294 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Bucharest ROMPRES</LOCATION>, 8/4/1994 -- After significant 
contacts with Romanian officials and a concert at <ORGANIZATION>Radio Hall</ORGANIZATION> 
conducted by Belgian Foreign Minister <PERSON>Willy Claes</PERSON>, the chief 
diplomat was received by Romanian president <PERSON>Ion Iliescu</PERSON> on 8 
<DATE>April</DATE> at the <ORGANIZATION>Cotroceni Palace</ORGANIZATION>. 
  Summing up his discussion with the Romanian head of state 
and 
other officials, <PERSON>Willy Claes</PERSON> said that the political statement 
he signed in <LOCATION>Bucharest</LOCATION> offered a framework "comprehensive 
enough" to allow for the development of relations, especially 
legal and economic. The Belgian foreign minister said that when 
there are sufficient guarantees of stability in <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION>, Belgian 
investors would not hesitate to do business in <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION>. 
  The same day, the Belgian foreign minister had an interview 
with <ORGANIZATION>Chamber of Deputies Speaker Adrian Nastase</ORGANIZATION>, during which he 
said <LOCATION>Western Europe</LOCATION> did not intend to treat countries in Central 
and <LOCATION>Eastern Europe</LOCATION> differently than any others. 
  Minister <PERSON>Willy Claes</PERSON> had to cut his Romanian visit short 
because of recent events in <LOCATION>Rwanda</LOCATION> which cost the lives of 
several Belgian UN officers stationed in that country. He left 
<LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION> in the afternoon of <DATE>April 8</DATE>. 

</TEXT>

